Governor Lee Kinyanjui urged residents to be hopeful, as 2021, he said will bring better tidings.
"We thank God we have made it. We step into the New Year with the hope of better tidings for our county and nation,” he said.
Overcome challenges
Moses Esekon, the national chairperson of Vijana Tuomoke na BBI, said: “I urge my fellow youth to avoid drugs and excessive drinking. I appeal to the youth to play a key role in championing the youth agenda by electing fellow youths in the county and national assemblies in the coming year”.
In her New Year message, Bishop Margaret Mwihaki of Kings Assembly urged Kenyans to put their hopes on God to overcome challenges ahead.
“The just ended pandemic year was tough and as a country we lost many people, the economy collapsed and I urge Kenyans to pray hard for God’s blessings,” said Bishop Mwihaki



