Worship places
In Nakuru town, hundreds of residents turned up in places of worship to pray for people who died from Covid-19.
At Prophet David Owuor's Repentance and Holiness Kings Outreach church, hundreds of worshippers started streaming in as early as 5pm.
“We gathered her to pray that God intervenes and heals Kenya and the World in 2021,” said Mr Vitalis Omondi.
Places of worship in informal settlements also attracted hundreds of worshippers.
In Nakuru town, there were no firework celebrations like in previous years. Kenyatta Avenue remained deserted and only police officers patrolled the streets.
Police led by Nakuru Town East Police commander Ellena Kabukuru arrested residents who contravened curfew rules.
However, revelers at the Platinum 7D Lounge defied the curfew order to enjoy their favourite drinks as they ushered in the new year.
Empty malls
The shopping malls in the town were virtually empty, a clear evidence of harsh economic times.
However, bookshops and uniform shops were a beehive of activity as parents packed the outlets to buy school items ahead of the reopening of schools on January 4.
“This is a tough year for me. I lost my job as a shop attendant due to Coronavirus. The little money I’m spending to buy school uniforms and other items, I was paid when my services were terminated in October,” said Joseph Kinuthia.



