Evade police
In Taita Taveta County, Kenyans spent night dodging police, with some opting to cross the border to celebrate New Year in Tanzania, where there are less-restrictive Covid-19 measures. 
Hundreds of Kenyans spent their time at the Holili border in Taveta.
Taking advantage of a favourable foreign exchange rate, they extended their party before returning to their country in a convoy of motorbikes singing songs condemning the introduction of curfew rules and stringent Covid-19 measures.
"We have strong currency compared to Tanzania and we can afford to buy what we want. We cannot afford to stay in the house as we cross new year that is why we had to go our neighboring country," said John Mwalekwa.
He added: "With Sh1500, we can buy what we want and with financial constraints as a result of Covid-19, that was only way we could do it best. We organized ourselves and moved in number and we are happy we are back to plan how our children will go back to school".
At home
In Mombasa, many residents spent their New Year's Eve at home like many other Kenyans in compliance with the curfew rule.
Some took time to make merry at hotels with friends hours to the countdown into the new year.
Residents watched firework displays at Fort Jesus and EnglishPoint Marina where they opted to have the fireworks display at around 9:30pm.



